      <p>This metabolic shift toward sugar metabolism is not surprising since it is known that cancer cells in general [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B10">10</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B11">11</xref>], and glioblastoma cells in particular [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B11">11</xref>], depend on the conversion of glucose to lactate in the presence of oxygen (Warburg effect [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B12">12</xref>]). It has also been shown that shutdown or down-regulation of the glycolysis pathway in glioblastoma is associated with cell death [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B13">13</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B14">14</xref>].</p>
      <p>We find that mean measurements for glycolytic genes are, on average, larger in the STS compared to the LTS phenotype (Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">1</xref>) and that there are more gene copies in STSs. Since reduced glycolysis (and sugar usage) promotes GBM cell death, we speculate that there might be an association between patient survival and efficient sugar metabolism, which is being detected by the integrative approach but missed by conventional analysis of each data type separately.</p>
